As with cryptococcosis in humans, cats, and dogs,2, 5, 7 the 2 most common species reported in ferrets is C neoformans and C gattii (Table 1
). Of the 13 cases that reported the infectious species, 6 ferrets were infected with C neoformans
6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11 and 6 were infected with C gatti.7, 12, 13, 14 In the 3 cases that the variant was listed for C neoformans, it was always var. grubii.7, 10, 11 The infectious species was not explicitly listed in 2 ferrets15; they were included in a report of a 2003 outbreak of Cryptococcus in Canada, where other animals and humans were infected with both C neoformans and C gattii (see Table 1).
